<bdy>

<b>Harry Bell Measures</b> (1862 - 1940) was architect for a number of English "improved" housing developments for working men, such as the <financial_institution wordnetid="108054721" confidence="0.8">
<foundation wordnetid="108406486" confidence="0.8">
<charity wordnetid="108406619" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../412/4930412.xml">
Rowton Houses</link></institution>
</charity>
</foundation>
</financial_institution>
 in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../867/17867.xml">
London</link></village>
 and <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../056/13882056.xml">
Birmingham</link></village>
. He also designed the original station buildings for the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../789/72789.xml">
Central London Railway</link>, now the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../789/72789.xml">
Central Line</link> of <body wordnetid="107965085" confidence="0.8">
<social_group wordnetid="107950920" confidence="0.8">
<railway wordnetid="104048568" confidence="0.8">
<enterprise wordnetid="108056231" confidence="0.8">
<carrier wordnetid="108057633" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<business wordnetid="108061042" confidence="0.8">
<administration wordnetid="108164585" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../839/17839.xml">
London Underground</link></administration>
</business>
</group>
</carrier>
</enterprise>
</railway>
</social_group>
</body>
, that opened on <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../911/15911.xml">
30 July</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../653/34653.xml">
1900</link>. <p>

Measures was later the Director of Barrack Construction for the British <structure wordnetid="104341686" confidence="0.8">
<building wordnetid="102913152" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../472/274472.xml">
War Office</link></artifact>
</building>
</structure>
 and was responsible for buildings such as Dreghorn and <foundation wordnetid="113790712" confidence="0.8">
<footing wordnetid="113790912" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../298/2475298.xml">
Redford Barracks</link></footing>
</foundation>
 in <site wordnetid="108651247" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../602/9602.xml">
Edinburgh</link></site>
.</p>

